column4: Cardinale et al., J Anim Ecol 2006
column12: Animalia:Arthropoda:Insecta:Coleopera (Harmonia axyridis, Coccinella septumpunctata, Coleomagilla maculata)
column20: University of Wisconsins Arlington Research Farm in south central Wisconsin
column42: Authors used an 'additive' design that intentionally confounds predator richness and abundance so that one can detect deviations from the additive expectation (i.e. non-additive interactions among predators).  Thus, even while Figure 1a shows that aphid densities declined as predator richness increased, increasing predator diversity actually led to an increase in prey density due to antagonistic interactions among predators (Figure 1b).  Thus, the appropriate test for a 'diversity effect' is the proportional deviation in prey density in the 3 predator species system from the expected values.  Expected values were calculated from the multiplicative risk model (1-P1)*(1-P2)*(1-P3) ... where Pi is the proportion of aphids killed by each of the 3 predator species when alone, calculted as the deviation from controls.  Effects of predator richness are reported relative to predator monocultures.
column222: Study reports statistical tests showing non-additive enemy interactions, but it's not clear how to translate this into effects metrics.

Thus, the appropriate test for a 'diversity effect' is the proportional deviation in prey density in the 3 predator species system from the expected values.  Expected values were calculated from the multiplicative risk model (1-P1)*(1-P2)*(1-P3) ... where Pi is the proportion of aphids killed by each of the 3 predator species when alone, calculted as the deviation from controls.  Effects of predator richness are reported relative to predator monocultures.
column222: Study reports statistical tests showing non-additive enemy interactions, but it's not clear how to translate this into effects metrics.
